# Summary

The Rank-Nullity Theorem (or the Fundamental Theorem of Linear Algebra) relates the kernel and image of a linear 
transformation of both vector and linear spaces. In particular, for any $n \times m$ matrix $A$
$$ \text{dim}(\text{ker}\;A) + \text{dim}(\text{im}\;A) = m. $$

Similarly, it $T$ is a linear transformation from linear spaces $V$ to $W$ and $V$ is finite dimensional, then the 
Rank-Nullity Theorem again holds: 
$$ \text{dim}(V) = \text{rank}(T) + \text{nullity}(T) = \text{dim}(\text{im}\;T) + \text{dim}(\text{ker}\;T). $$

We prove the above in the context of just linear spaces.

<div class="proof">

First note that $\text{ker}(T)$ must be finite dimensional since $\text{ker}(T)$ is a subspace of $V$, implying 
$\text{dim}(\text{ker}\;T) \leq \text{dim}(V)$.[^1]  
Similarly, $\text{im}(T)$ is finitely generated by the columns of finite dimensional subspace $V$. 
Thus $\text{im}(T)$ is also finite dimensional.[^2]

Consider a basis $(\inflate{v}{n})$ of $\text{ker}(T)$ where $n = \text{nullity}(T)$, and basis $(\inflate{w}{r})$ of 
$\text{im}(T)$, where $r = \text{rank}(T)$. Consider elements $\inflate{u}{r}$ in $V$ such that $T(u_i) = w_i$ for 
$i = \inflate{u}{r}$.

- First we show that $\inflate{u}{r}, \inflate{v}{n}$ are linearly independent. Consider relation 
$c_1u_1 + \cdots + c_ru_r + d_1v_1 + \cdots + d_nv_n = 0$. Then
$$\begin{align*}
  T(0) = 0 &= T(c_1u_1 + \cdots + c_ru_r + d_1v_1 + \cdots + d_nv_n) \\
           &= T(c_1u_1) + \cdots + T(c_ru_r) + T(d_1v_1) + \cdots + T(d_nv_n) \\
           &= c_1T(u_1) + \cdots + c_rT(u_r) + d_1T(v_1) + \cdots + d_nT(v_n) \\
           &= c_1w_1 + \cdots + c_rw_r + d_1(0) + \cdots + d_n(0)\\
           &= c_1w_1 + \cdots + c_rw_r
\end{align*}$$
Since $\inflate{w}{r}$ is linearly independent, only the trivial relation holds.<br />

- Next we show that $\inflate{u}{r}, \inflate{v}{n}$ span $V$. Let $v$ be any element in $V$, and note 
$$ T(v) = d_1w_1 + \cdots + d_rw_r\text{.} $$
We also note that
$$\begin{align*}
  0 &= T(v - d_1u_1 - \cdots - d_ru_r)\\
    &= T(v) - d_1T(u_1) - \cdots - d_rT(u_r)\\
    &= d_1w_1 + \cdots + d_rw_r - d_1w_1 - \cdots d_rw_r
\end{align*}$$
so $v-d_1u_1-\cdots-d_ru_r$ is in the kernel of $T$. Therefore $v-d_1u_1-\cdots-d_ru_r$ can be written as a linear 
combination of $\inflate{v}{n}$:
$$\begin{align*}
  &\qquad v-d_1u_1-\cdots-d_ru_r = c_1v_1 + \cdots + c_nv_n\\
  &\Rightarrow v = c_1v_1 + \cdots + c_nv_n + d_1u_1 + \cdots + d_ru_r
\end{align*}$$

Therefore, since $\inflate{u}{r}, \inflate{v}{n}$ are linearly independent and span $V$, these
$r + n$ elements form a basis of $V$. Thus $$\text{dim}(V) = \text{rank}(T) + \text{nullity}(T)\text{.} $$

